etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Hall Caine (1853–1931), novelist. From Manx jeeill, jeell damage, cognate with Irish díobháil damage, loss (Early Irish dígbál, dígbáil diminution, loss, damage), verbal noun of do-gaib takes away, diminishes from do-, unstressed variant of dí- + -gaib, combining form of gaibid takes (from the same Indo-European base as post-classical Latin habēre)
